Nitpick: 3. Capitalize the subject line is a rule here: https://chris.beams.io/posts/git-commit/#limit-50

It seems odd that this parameter is now required on log entry?  What about for systems that don't support notifying the service provider?  Adding this property unconditionally in redfish implies that support, even for systems that don't have that capability.  I suspect some level of dbus interface changes will need to happen to either make this optional, or to convey whether or not this is supported on the given system.

I added the author and reviews of the D-Bus interface. 
https://gerrit.openbmc-project.xyz/c/openbmc/phosphor-dbus-interfaces/+/42972

bmcweb is following PDI here.

This property is added as part of version v1_9_0 of log entry. If the property is not supported it will return false(default). If the interface does not support this property then we don't enter if condition and we will not evaluate but return false. I am not sure if that is intended or not. I will ask other experts to comment.

> This property is added as part of version v1_9_0 of log entry. If the property is not supported it will return false(default).

"not supported" is supposed to be property not present, not false, hence this comment.

> If the interface does not support this property then we don't enter if condition and we will not evaluate but return false. I am not sure if that is intended or not. I will ask other experts to comment.

This is the conflict here;  there's no way in the interface definition to convey "Service provider not supported" which is required for systems that don't support reporting back to a service provider.

Ed, I get your point, but I will need someone else to answer. I think if a system supports v1_9_0 then it will have this property in its interface and its left to the end user to support it or not. I am nit expert here. i need someone else to explain.

Seems like there are two options...

1) if the check on line 1410 is never successful, then the property wasn't there so leave it out of the redfish response

2) Turn the d-bus property into an enum with 3 values - NotApplicable, Notify, NotNotify

> Seems like there are two options...
> 
> 1) if the check on line 1410 is never successful, then the property wasn't there so leave it out of the redfish response

This would imply that we now allow optional properties on dbus interfaces, which doesn't seem like it's maintainable in the long run.

> 
> 2) Turn the d-bus property into an enum with 3 values - NotApplicable, Notify, NotNotify

That seems reasonable to me for its simplicity in implementation.  nit: Maybe "NotSupported" instead for the enum?  "NotApplicable" might be confused with something like the service is disabled.

"NotSupported", "Notify", "NotNotified" seems reasonable to me. 
Another choice would be moving this to a different interface and only supported systems can implement that interface

What's going on with this?  I see a new patch set today after 3-4 months with functionally no change.

> This would imply that we now allow optional properties on dbus interfaces, which doesn't seem like it's maintainable in the long run.

There really isn't such a thing from a dbus perspective.

> What's going on with this? 

This question was never answered.  Please only mark things "done" when the discussion has concluded, or the requested change has been made.

The dbus interface and all implementations have been moved to an enum with the default value of NotSupported. 
When the value isNotSupported, this property is left off Redfish. Can you add this to the commit msg and maybe add as a comment as well?

It's interesting that the service validator didn't catch this.  This parameter in the schemas is "ServiceProviderNotified".  Can you please provide your test results so we can triage this failure in the service validator.  Considering that you ran this test and it passed, there might be a bug in the validator that we need to get fixed.

From https://redfish.dmtf.org/schemas/v1/LogEntry.v1_13_0.json

                "ServiceProviderNotified": {
                    "description": "Indicates if the log entry has been sent to the service provider.",
                    "longDescription": "This property shall contain an indication if the log entry has been sent to the service provider.",
                    "readonly": true,
                    "type": [
                        "boolean",
                        "null"
                    ],
                    "versionAdded": "v1_9_0"
                },

This is an oversight. I learned lesson. Fixed the code.
Redfish validator is not checking EventLog Entries 2 - 99. I was testing by  changing EventLog Entry 99 as described in commit message.
Redfish validator failed when I changed the EventLog Entry 102.
nit, like we do elsewhere, please do *notifyAction.
LGTM.  Gunnar to do final signoff

notify is not added in all versions of the log interface.  Per DBUS_USAGE.md, it should not be required unless we've updated all implementations.  I don't see that documentation in your commit message.
